Spotify Earnings
----------------

From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-11-12/spotify=
-beats-subscriber-margin-estimates-even-as-ad-sales-lag ) :

Spotify Technology SA shares jumped Wednesday morning after the music strea=
ming service reported third-quarter growth in subscribers and profit margin=
s, saying lower marketing and personnel costs helped overcome a tough clima=
te for advertising. Paying subscribers grew to 252 million, the Stockholm-b=
ased company said Tuesday in a statement, beating analysts=E2=80=99 estimat=
es of 250.1 million. Total monthly active users increased to 640 million, a=
lso exceeding estimates.

The company is showing the benefits of workforce cuts taken late last year,=
 along with the tailwind from continued growth. Its gross margin, a measure=
 of profitability, widened to 31.1%, topping Wall Street expectations, and =
its operating income surged to =E2=82=AC454 million. Revenue for the quarte=
r increased 19% to =E2=82=AC3.99 billion, missing the =E2=82=AC4.03 billion=
 average of analysts=E2=80=99 estimates. Advertising revenue increased 6%, =
held back by low prices in its music business and podcasts.

The most striking thing about Spotify=E2=80=99s results is the extent to wh=
ich the company is completely reliant on subscription revenue for growth; n=
ew CFO Christian Luiga reported on the earnings call ( https://seekingalpha=
.com/article/4736645-spotify-technology-s-spot-q3-2024-earnings-call-transc=
ript ) :

Turning then to the quarterly results. Quarter three marked another strong =
quarter for the business. MAU grew by 14 million to 640 million, and we add=
ed 6 million net subscribers, finishing at 252 million. Both MAU and subscr=
iber growth outperformed our guidance by 1 million. Total revenue grew 21% =
year-on-year on a constant-currency basis to EUR4 billion. Premium revenue =
rose 24% year-on-year on a constant-currency basis, driven by continued sub=
scriber growth and ARPU acceleration associated with price increases. Our a=
dvertising business saw currency-neutral growth of 7% year-on-year, reflect=
ing another quarter of volatile market spending on brand-related campaigns.

=E2=80=9CCompletely reliant=E2=80=9D is actually understating it, given tha=
t subscriptions exceeded the company=E2=80=99s overall growth number. The k=
ey factor driving subscription revenue growth is Spotify=E2=80=99s ability =
to raise prices. Luiga said:

With respect to subscriber net additions, the very low levels of churn that=
 we expect in the six markets where we=E2=80=99ve recently announced price =
increases is also incorporated into our quarter four outlook. This is consi=
stent with what we had seen historically. We have also incorporated our ong=
oing actions to drive better subscriber monetization. Although new pricing =
will contribute towards ARPU growth in quarter four overall, we expect the =
lapping of 2023 year=E2=80=99s price increases that we had in 63 markets th=
at they will lead to an approximately 400 basis point moderation of a year-=
on-year ARPU growth on a constant currency basis in our revenue outlook.

CEO Daniel Ek sounded a lot like Netflix executives while discussing the co=
mpany=E2=80=99s strategy of increasing value and then harvesting that value=
 through these price increases:

As you kind of go into the later part of the year and certainly 2026, we ar=
e looking at new initiatives too. So the story of Spotify, if you know us b=
y now through our history of a public company has really been one where we =
constantly keep innovating and we keep pushing the envelope of what our con=
sumers are expecting for us. And we really do that through that lens of the=
 value-to-price ratio that we keep talking about. How do we constantly and =
relentlessly add more and more value to our consumers because we know that =
if we focus on that, eventually price will be there for us to take as I thi=
nk we=E2=80=99ve proven this year.

A lot of that value increase has come in the form of non-music audio conten=
t like podcasts and audiobooks, which has in turn decreased the share of re=
venue collected by music labels. This is helping Spotify look more like a t=
ech company ( https://stratechery.com/2018/lessons-from-spotify/?access_tok=
en=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsIn=
R5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJI=
S0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ=
5LmNvbS8yMDE4L2xlc3NvbnMtZnJvbS1zcG90aWZ5LyJdfSwiZXhwIjoxNzM1MjExODAzLCJpYX=
QiOjE3MzI2MTk4MDMsImlzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8vYXBpLnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZS9vYXV0aCIsI=
nNjb3BlIjoiZmVlZDpyZWFkIGFydGljbGU6cmVhZCBhc3NldDpyZWFkIGNhdGVnb3J5OnJlYWQg=
ZW50aXRsZW1lbnRzIiwic3ViIjoiUnNldVlFOGpnSGVQcFdKZjFmQWI0QyIsInVzZSI6ImFjY2V=
zcyJ9.RX48sOS4ffQeIpb90-lES2FxKYzExSLKSJm1ZTD9jWhjyCONS_Hyi9AaoxhqD0ICGqCk7=
leoQphz3PYU4JGHDOq8xeM_e91XhpxXiS_wuuG5yaBHOSgUmMzj336LAcuaSWLiME_gQFnlgTvn=
k9ljtfu7Q6giIADzUC9mOUlQPfMQjB7d5yc6L2vkxd1PWmtWxtJjyaZu9LKTIFQgiYm1JYSjWv6=
ozq2x3yVqV0rHpnvzbSpdC_bCpKVBQJysvTQ6gonNXLVPgSEEcGyELvUXI0-ZT8Jyp7FiTf3VzF=
5X1Bo6xPAoZEz9KmWhvP9NrH0npBeB-uryfCzUGMBEcbLo6A ) ; Luiga discussed how Sp=
otify is seeing margin improvement through increased leverage on its non-re=
venue sharing costs:

The gross margin improved in a way that it was a continuation of quarter tw=
o. I mean, we have a very good marketplace program that actually is develop=
ing well and has improved the gross margin. We also have streaming and deli=
very costs and I have to add also payment costs that we are scaling on. And=
 on top of that, we have the US publishing rate favorability that comes thr=
ough our books. And that is the reason for quarter two and that=E2=80=99s t=
he reason for quarter three improvement.

Given this, one of the analyst questions of Ek hinted at the desire of musi=
c labels to change the deal:

*There=E2=80=99s been speculation that the record labels would like to move=
 to a per subscriber pricing model similar to cable TV networks. From a Spo=
tify perspective, what are the pros and cons from moving from variable to f=
ixed pricing?*

*DE:* Yeah, I=E2=80=99m not sure I can comment so much on that speculation.=
 But to say that we have a very healthy relationship with our partners and =
we=E2=80=99re constantly discussing what the future of the model will be an=
d how this can provide growth for the music ecosystem.

You can imagine a world where Spotify would take that deal; it=E2=80=99s a =
world where the company never expands beyond music, much as cable networks =
are, well, nothing but TV. Imagine, however, if the cable networks also own=
ed YouTube; that=E2=80=99s a better analogy for Spotify=E2=80=99s current s=
tate, and it=E2=80=99s hard to imagine a diversified audio company paying o=
ne subset of its suppliers a per-subscriber fee: music labels need to earn =
their share, just like everyone else.

Spotify=E2=80=99s Video Plans
---------------------

Speaking of YouTube, these earnings provide useful context for the company=
=E2=80=99s announcements the following day; from the Wall Street Journal ( =
https://www.wsj.com/business/media/spotify-takes-aim-at-youtube-in-battle-f=
or-podcasts-ad6db6a7 ) :

Spotify is trying to break YouTube=E2=80=99s stronghold on video podcasts. =
As fans increasingly flock to videos of star hosts interacting with their g=
uests during interviews, Spotify wants to persuade more podcasters to make =
videos for its own platform in addition to YouTube. Spotify plans to start =
paying hosts who make popular videos and meet a certain viewing threshold, =
and will soon offer premium subscribers a way to watch shows such as =E2=80=
=9CThe Joe Rogan Experience=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CAnything Goes with Emma C=
hamberlain=E2=80=9D without ads. It currently allows hosts to upload podcas=
t videos, but doesn=E2=80=99t offer such payments.

While Spotify is home to some of the most listened-to podcasts, there are s=
igns that its dominance in the exploding medium is waning as more listeners=
 watch, or listen to, their favorite shows on YouTube. The Google-owned pla=
tform has become a central part of many young people=E2=80=99s entertainmen=
t diet and shares ad revenue with creators who post videos, which incentivi=
zes them to post ever more content=E2=80=A6

YouTube is taking over podcasts ( https://www.wsj.com/business/media/spotif=
y-takes-aim-at-youtube-in-battle-for-podcasts-ad6db6a7 )

=E2=80=A6Beginning in January, Spotify plans to offer premium subscribers i=
n the U.S., U.K., Australia and Canada ad-free viewing of video podcasts. I=
t is betting that the uninterrupted experience coupled with its powerful di=
scovery algorithms will drive greater consumption of video podcasts on the =
platform. The offering, which takes out ads inserted into episodes but woul=
d leave host-read messages, could also differentiate Spotify=E2=80=99s podc=
ast videos from those on YouTube, where users have to pay more for ad-free =
viewing. For hosts, Spotify=E2=80=99s new incentives offer a fresh stream o=
f revenue. While Spotify expects to pay more than YouTube on a per-view bas=
is, it said YouTube has many more users and will likely continue to pay mor=
e in total to creators. YouTube pays out most video creators a 55% share of=
 revenue of the ads it sells against a show. Spotify estimates a show that =
draws 1 million to 2 million views in a month would earn about $50,000 via =
the new model.

For all of the praise Spotify deserves for the diversification of their off=
ering, this is obviously a very concerning chart for the company; it=E2=80=
=99s not just that YouTube is getting listenership that Spotify would like =
to have, it=E2=80=99s that YouTube is the podcast platform of choice for th=
e next generation, which, over time, might convert into the overall audio p=
latform of choice. To put it another way, Spotify needs to lean into video =
to preempt YouTube moving into Spotify=E2=80=99s dominance of pocket time. =
Ek told The Verge ( https://www.theverge.com/2024/11/15/24297466/spotify-ce=
o-daniel-ek-interview-video-podcasts-youtube ) :

What=E2=80=99s really interesting about Spotify is the moments during the d=
ay [in which] we do really well. That=E2=80=99s where we=E2=80=99re uniquel=
y positioned against many others. The consumption of Spotify tends to be mo=
re longform because people tend to go in and out. They tend to watch it, te=
nd to put it down to the pocket. And this will work seamlessly on Spotify. =
The default experience of these other platforms is you sit there and are gl=
ued, which also means disrupting all your other experiences.

What Spotify needs to do is get video-only podcasts onto the platform and i=
nto those Spotify-dominated moments of the day; that means the company is r=
eady to pay-up. From the company=E2=80=99s press release ( https://newsroom=
.spotify.com/2024-11-13/spotify-unveils-uninterrupted-video-podcasts-audien=
ce-driven-payments-and-the-new-spotify-for-creators-platform/ ) :

=E2=80=9CSpotify Premium has long set the standard for listening on any dev=
ice,=E2=80=9D shared Spotify founder and CEO Daniel Ek. =E2=80=9CBy deliver=
ing a best-in-class video offering uninterrupted by ad breaks, combined wit=
h Spotify=E2=80=99s flexibility and ubiquity, we can provide an experience =
for your audience that is superior to any platform. And by giving you, the =
creators, another path to monetization beyond ads, we=E2=80=99re freeing yo=
u up to spend more time doing what you love: creating.=E2=80=9D

So, what=E2=80=99s in store for creators? They=E2=80=99ll be part of a new =
and industry-leading audience-driven payout model for Premium video consump=
tion, and their fans will now get video content uninterrupted by ads. Spoti=
fy=E2=80=99s Partner Program, a brand-new monetization program for creators=
 hosted with Spotify, will launch that allows creators to earn more for the=
ir audio and video content. This program will offer both audience-driven pa=
youts from our premium video revenue and an Ads component.

The details are notable: a close read of the Spotify for Creators monetizat=
ion page ( https://creators.spotify.com/features/monetization ) reveals tha=
t while both video and audio podcasts can earn a revenue share from ads, on=
ly video podcasts can get a share of subscription revenue. Video podcasts, =
after all, particularly video podcasts that are YouTube only, are what Spot=
ify wants.

There is a link here to the excerpt above about music labels; specifically,=
 an easy way to identify Spotify=E2=80=99s relative power over a supplier i=
s to look at these sorts of details. When Spotify started they were complet=
ely beholden to music labels, who extracted their pound of flesh by demandi=
ng a revenue share; now that Spotify has diversified its content the music =
labels want a different deal, which Spotify can trivially dismiss. Audio po=
dcasts, meanwhile, were already freely available, which means that Spotify =
hasn=E2=80=99t had to give them anything to get them to come onto its platf=
orm =E2=80=94 reach was enough. If those audio podcasts want to help grow S=
potify=E2=80=99s advertising business, Spotify is happy to share that reven=
ue, but that=E2=80=99s it.

In this view video podcasts are much more like music labels in Spotify=E2=
=80=99s early days: just as getting music label contracts was existential t=
o Spotify then, it=E2=80=99s clear that the company sees convincing YouTube=
-only video podcasts to move to its platform as an existential threat, whic=
h is why they are getting the same deal.

Spotify=E2=80=99s Ad Business
---------------------

So about that struggling advertising business: management was asked if they=
 might institute an ad-supported subscription tier instead of being free wi=
th advertising. Ek said that wasn=E2=80=99t a good idea because of radio:

We=E2=80=99re always open to considering how we evolve our opportunity. And=
 as I mentioned before, we=E2=80=99re always thinking about what does creat=
or needs and what does consumers want and we=E2=80=99re really trying to fi=
nd win-wins between the two. One of the challenges and specifically why mus=
ic is not analogous to video, however, that=E2=80=99s good for investors to=
 be aware of in music specifically, because of the regulatory rights enviro=
nment, you are with radio and other things, there=E2=80=99s a lot of ad-sup=
ported music available out there in the marketplace. This is not something =
that=E2=80=99s likely going to change. And so as you think about that, ther=
e is a very, very different industry dynamic in music as compared to, say, =
something like video where we=E2=80=99ve obviously followed what=E2=80=99s =
happening with the ad-supported tiers with fees involved, et cetera. So we=
=E2=80=99re always open. We are always discussing with our partners and wit=
h consumers=E2=80=99 needs, thinking about how do we create the best possib=
le proposition. But it is a very different environment than in video. So I =
don=E2=80=99t think we can just overlay what happened in video and say, hey=
, let=E2=80=99s do the same thing in music because it=E2=80=99s a very, ver=
y different regulatory environment and very different industry environment.

This seems reasonable, and also highlights why Spotify=E2=80=99s ad busines=
s has struggled; radio has both national buys from brand buyers, and also l=
ocal ads who target individual stations. Spotify, meanwhile, has by-and-lar=
ge been brand only; Luiga explained:

I just wanted to remind ourselves about the journey we are on also. Our ad =
business today have been heavily reliant on direct sales and top funnel bra=
nd spend. And therefore, I mean, what we=E2=80=99ve seen over the years the=
 type of ads business that we built has an exposure to macro trends. So wit=
h this, we have now diversified and changed our platform and built this Spo=
tify Ad Exchange, and moving on with the Trade Desk as a test pilot. What w=
e do see is that 2025 will be a year of testing and trying out this and we =
will see the impact going into 2026. It is early days. We are new to the au=
ction environment and it=E2=80=99s important that we are very deliberate an=
d careful about how we roll out the supply into these channels, but we also=
 in the same time, very excited that this will help us to change.

It=E2=80=99s honestly kind of surprising that Spotify is only now getting i=
nto programmatic ads; my big takeaway is that I previously overestimated th=
e advertising component of the company=E2=80=99s shift into podcasting and =
underestimated Spotify=E2=80=99s desire to diversify listening away from mu=
sic labels. To me the former was always the bigger opportunity ( https://st=
ratechery.com/2019/spotifys-podcast-aggregation-play/?access_token=3DeyJhbG=
ciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXV=
CJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1N=
od1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMD=
E5L3Nwb3RpZnlzLXBvZGNhc3QtYWdncmVnYXRpb24tcGxheS8iXX0sImV4cCI6MTczNTIxMTgwM=
ywiaWF0IjoxNzMyNjE5ODAzLCJpc3MiOiJodHRwczovL2FwaS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUvb2F1=
dGgiLCJzY29wZSI6ImZlZWQ6cmVhZCBhcnRpY2xlOnJlYWQgYXNzZXQ6cmVhZCBjYXRlZ29yeTp=
yZWFkIGVudGl0bGVtZW50cyIsInN1YiI6IlJzZXVZRThqZ0hlUHBXSmYxZkFiNEMiLCJ1c2UiOi=
JhY2Nlc3MifQ.AsbzFZCStvEdFZuuHrvrjKxGZCi44YLDei-JaMXfCDxmpquR_Mxx0oUF-BIgIY=
JLKv0tRCzy-WtJoglggiNM3clZ1CitG5uvX_zZ5JdPYhTiy8s4w9M8p4cupnShrKW8mBfPEG95u=
L44a6ZuOnK7XTb8WPETbFrbVQe3D0uNgoH4EJLDk9eSkhbTfzZwLumUlQVbWUHNKNoXPGAR7Fnn=
bf03_M4wjATy4eetRZeDTpSfEKuOCmFE_Udj2Ww9fRT3gfSJzBdkipV6qSkbl7IqrcnKJ0O959F=
wyBKQAWvMTtpO1z0bvsnU8YsNqTkec_FwcbsrKgCneG8-wou2Cz2h-A ) , but the company=
=E2=80=99s ability to monetize subscribers in part by reducing its reliance=
